{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6eb5dcb2-2c43-40f5-b646-6db021a96a64","content":"Here's the approach for tracing .NET 8 in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect a CPU trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### To get the file off the pod\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives live CPU %, GC, thread pool stats — useful before committing to a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool` isn't on the PATH after install, the default tools path on Windows is `%USERPROFILE%\\.dotnet\\tools`. Also ensure the SDK or runtime version in the container supports the tool version you're installing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b3335a5a-5247-4d56-860e-df24ea7235b7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":426,"requestId":"A0D5:306175:BBFAA4:E93C3F:6A012FFC"},"id":"7068cd99-339d-45f3-bb39-b38e87b40f3a","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:25:26.572Z","parentId":"f1893a8c-c262-417d-ad73-305ec7bbdc0f"}
